<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870417-0099 </DOCNO><HL> Litton, Bath IronGet Navy ContractorsFor Missile Cruisers</HL><DD> 04/17/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> LIT MD GE GM UIS LOR NOC ITTAEROSPACE (ARO)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ingalls Shipbuilding, a unit of Litton Industries Inc., received a $368 million Navy contract for construction of two guided missile cruisers.    The Navy also awarded a $236 million contract to Bath Iron Works Corp. to construct one guided missile cruiser.    Work on all three of these cruisers is to be completed by April 1992.    In other contracts awarded yesterday, Northrop Corp. won a $188.5 million Air Force contract for missile-guidance equipment.    ITT Corp. received a $71.2 million Navy contract for shipboard radar systems.    Units of General Electric Co. were issued Air Force contracts totaling $47.6 million to improve aircraft engine components and for flight tests of an aircraft sensor system.    General Defense Corp. received a $41.1 million Army contract for tank ammunition.    Electronic Data Systems Corp., a unit of General Motors Corp., got Army contracts of $37.3 million for maintenance for the Defense Department's enrollment eligibility reporting system.    Loral Corp. received a $20.6 million Air Force contract for automatic test equipment.    Units of McDonnell Douglas Corp. were awarded Air Force contracts of $16.4 million for aerial refueling equipment and F15 aircraft flight test support.    Unisys Corp. won a $10.2 million Air Force contract for C-130 aircraft radar improvements. </TEXT></DOC>